n eunuch officials and sixteen male and female members of the royal family. Titles of their pictures held in the palace collection are listed for each artist. These 6,396 paintings testify to the visual culture experienced by viewers of the twelfth century. The author's Introduction analyzes the Catalogue as a source of evidence about the formation of the Song-dynasty palace collection and argues that the majority of its pictures were already in the collection before Huizong's reign, as a result of conquest, confiscation, tribute, gift culture, collecting by earlier emperors, and the production of academy artists and regular officials at the Song court. Under Huizong's reign, around a thousand other pictures were added to the Catalogue through acquisition and reattribution.Open access edition funded by the National Endowment for the Humanities.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPainterszChinaxHistoryySong-Yuan dynasties, 960-1368xBiographyvSources. 0aPainting, ChinesexCatalogsvEarly works to 1800. 0aPainting, ChineseySong-Yuan dynasties, 960-1368vSources. 0aPeintreszChinexHistoirey960-1368 (Dynasties des Song et des Yuan)xBiographiesvSources. 0aPeinture chinoisey960-1368 (Dynasties des Song et des Yuan)vSources. 4aArt History. 7aART / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aAsian art.  aDaoist and Buddhist art.  aSong-dynasty.1 aMcNair, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://www.degruyter.com